What other forms of fuel are you using besides the water power?
Well, as I stated, coal, and then there's not much coal in Texas, although the United States has
enough coal in it to take care of all the needs of the United States, say, for three or four hundred years.
By needs, I mean to make power and for any other use.
But there is a lot of lignite in Texas.
Now, lignite is what you call young coal.
It just hadn't been in the earth long enough to change to coal.
It's...
And therefore, it's not as good as coal from the standpoint of burning because it hadn't aged as long as coal has.
It still has some... And it takes...
It's not as economical a fuel as coal.
But since it's here in Texas, it's primarily in, say, from Bastrop towards Texarkana.
There's an area in there, the Aluminum Company of America has a tremendous lignite plant at Rockdale, and the Texas Power and Light Company buys power from it when they're not using it at the plant.
Then Texas Power and Light Company and Texas Utilities, Dallas Power and Light, are building or have built a big lignite plant on beyond Rockdale going towards Texarkana.
Now LCRA is trying to build it,
lignite plant near LaGrange or add to their coal plant but instead of burning coal burn lignite.

It's a little more difficult to burn lignite and but as I say since you don't have to ship it all the way from Wyoming it would be more economical and since people are so dependent on electric power this day and time for their mode of living
why it's up to the utilities to get them the power at the most economical rate that they can because otherwise the people couldn't use it.
And so the LCRA at the present time is considering building a lignite plant.
They are not considering building a nuclear plant at the present time.
And of course there are no other
fuels that are available.
They talk about them in the paper, about burning garbage and burning, I mean, solar power and wind power, windmills and things like that, but they're just sort of things that are way out and
And maybe they'll get some benefit out of it, maybe solar power after the year 2000 or beyond that, but not anytime soon.
So actually the only thing that they've got is to either burn oil, burn gas, or burn coal or burn lignite.
And oil is expensive and gas is expensive and
Although now that they're finding so much gas, there is a movement on to have Congress repeal the law saying that you can't build electric generating plants that will burn gas.
And they may do that.
If they do, why, they may go back to burning gas.
That's why all the plants in Texas were burning gas until just recently.
because there was plenty of gas in Texas, and it was a very economical fuel, it was a very clean fuel, and you don't have a lot of trash to dispose of after you burn it.
But that is the situation now insofar as
Electric power in the near future, I'd say in the next 10, 15, 20 years is going to have to come from coal, lignite, or gas, or nuclear power.
There's just not going to be any other source.
You mentioned that the SRA sells their energy to cities and townships and stuff like that.
Is their rates comparable to private companies?
Well, their rate was more economical in the early years.
From 1940 to 1965, I'd say 25 years, the people in Central Texas saved, by virtue of the LCRA rates, upward of all around $10 million, maybe up to $10 million a year.

average so they've served over saved over a quarter of a billion dollars in the 25 years that on electric rates that that money was able to stay in central texas and and spent by the people themselves rather than paid for electricity now after the uh oil embargo and when they
made them and the price of oil went so high and then gas went so high.
While the rates of LCRA are comparable to the rates of private utilities but they are still a little bit lower I understand.
I haven't kept up with it the last seven years.
You mentioned the other authorities that are in Texas.
Is the LCRA the largest one?
From the standpoint of business and income, it is much the largest because of the electric utility, electric business.
None of the other authorities have any electric power except the Brazos River Authority, and they sell their power at the dam.
They don't wholesale it to cities or rural electric cooperatives like the LCRA.
And they have a little power at Possum Kingdom Dam and then a little power at Whitney Dam.
But it doesn't amount to too much.
And their revenue then comes primarily from selling water for irrigation and for municipal uses.
And then they've gone in the sewerage business.
of building sewage plants for cities, small cities that couldn't afford to, the River Authority has built them and runs it for them.
And that's the same thing with the Trinity River Authority and others, but from standpoint of income, that of course is one of the great changes in the last few years.
When I was there, I think our income went up from about $2 million a year to about $20 million a year.
Well now, it's
well above $100 million and going up much more than that on account of the price of electricity having gone up so much.
Their power bill runs millions of dollars a month.
That's the basis of the electric load growing so much.
You mentioned that they're building more and more
plants, energy plants, are they expanding their output to different cities?
Is their area expanding?
The geographical area is not expanding, but the load is growing because the number of people in the area is expanding.
More people are moving into central Texas, and the population is growing, and the use of electric power is growing.
So what you have is that they still serve only the same places they served 20 years ago.
But it's like, just for example, the city of Austin.
20 years ago, probably had 100,000 people, 120,000.
Today it has nearly 400,000.
Well, it takes four times as much electricity.
Well, that's the same thing with the LCRA.
It is serving today much more than four times as much electricity to the same area that it served.
So it has to expand, otherwise the people wouldn't be able to buy electric power, and they'd have to go elsewhere to buy it, which they don't want to do, of course.
Is there any...
ill feelings or animosity between the LCRA and private companies?
Well, that's what I mentioned a while ago.
There was in the beginning, because the feeling was that the LCRA would be going into the business of the private utilities.
But that has died, I think, completely now in the last 20 or 30 years, well, since 1950.
And it came about, I think, by virtue of the fact they worked together so closely during the war.

uh and now all of them feel that each of them needs each other they're all interconnected they they if one of them loses a power plant while the other one uh sends the power in until they can get it fixed and all those kind of things so i don't think there's any there's just a feeling of working together the same kind of
feeling, though, that anybody who's in the same business is going to feel.

He's going to feel that his business is better, but he doesn't want the other one put out of business because he realizes that they're doing a good job and that also it's much better that they be there and doing what they're doing.
How does the LCRA handle flood situations in Texas?
What the LCRA has done and built up is they have numerous people located on farms and ranches all above the dams.
And they furnish them water gauges and rain gauges.
And whenever it rains more than an inch, they call the LCRA collect and tell them how much it has rained.
There are about, oh, I think 50 or more of those, probably more than that, rain gauges scattered all the way from Burn It Clear out in West Texas on various farms and ranches.
And then when the water gets to the creeks and then into a river, while we have people stationed that live there that go down and measure the river.
and say how much the river has risen, how many feet.

And then the LCRA has measured that so they know that if the San Salvador River at a certain place has risen 10 feet and is now 15 feet high, they know how much water that is and how much water it will put in the lake, let's say Lake Buckhannon, because that's where the San Salvador River comes into, if it runs for 24 hours.
And so what they have are rain gauge people that call in and tell them when they're raining.
And if it rains more than an inch, they call in on the first inch, and then every time it rains as much as another inch, they call in.
Now when it rains 10 or 12 inches, which causes the floods, a lot of times they can't call in on account of the rain, and we don't hear from them until after the rain is over.
But by then we know that there's a big rain.
Now, that was before the day of radar.

Now you have radar that scans the country, and the weathermen advise the LCRA, but we still have the rain gauges out on the farms, and they call in and say how much rain they have, whether the creeks are running, and then the people on the rivers, the San Salvador River, the Brady Creek, the Pecan Bow, the Concho Rivers, and the Llano Rivers, and the Pertinellas River,
They all call in and say how much water is coming down.
And when you're seeing some of those places, it takes the water two to three days to get to the lakes.
Just like when you release it here in Austin, it takes five days for it to go all the way down to the coast.
So we have to figure out the days.
We know how much water is coming.
We know how much water we can hold in the lakes.
And if necessary, we start releasing water, but try not to release any more than the river below us can hold, keeping in mind it's going to take five days for it to get to the coast.
So it's what it is.
It's based on plans and figures and calculations that have been made as to how much water is coming in and how much water you can let out without flooding people.
How exactly is the transition made from LCRA electricity to actual home electricity?

Well, what the LCRA does is it sells the electricity wholesale, except it does sell retail in Kerrville, San Marcos, and San Salvo because those towns voted that it wanted the LCRA to run their system.
But the LCRA sells wholesale to a town, say,
Brenham, and Brenham, the city buys it, and the city owns all the electric lines in the city.
And they then take, they have their own electric system, they're people working for them, and they take the power at the substation and deliver it.
It's delivered over their lines to the towns, I mean the cities, the stores, the filling stations, the schools, and they collect and they use that money to help run the city.
and build swimming pools and parks and other things.

And the LCRA sells to rural cooperatives and they take the power to the farms and the ranches and they collect for it and pay off their debts that they borrowed their money from the Rural Electric Administration in Washington and they're paying off their debts and pay their
expenses of their employees.

So what the LCRA does is generate the electricity and takes it to these cities, 29 of them, like Georgetown, San Salvador, Kerrville, and Burnett, and Llano, and all the others, and the rural electric cooperatives like the Blue Bonnet Co-op, the co-op down at Fayetteville,
Fayette County Co-op and San Bernard Co-op and all of them, it takes it to them at their substation.
Then they deliver it out to the people and collect for it.
And each one of them fixes its own retail rate.
So while the LCRA charges all of them the same for the electricity that's delivered to them, so much a kilowatt and so much a kilowatt hour,
The city or the cooperative can charge a different rate if it wants to, if it has to.
It depends on what the problems are in delivering it.
So some of the rates may be different in the cities and the co-ops than in others, but that's because of their own problems.
But the LCRA sells them all at the same price.
